\begin_layout Standard
Porosity plays a crucial role in petroleum engineering, particularly in
 the context of oil reservoirs.
 It refers to the amount of empty space within the reservoir rock that can
 store hydrocarbons such as oil and gas.
 The importance of porosity manifests in several key areas of the oil exploratio
n and production process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firstly, porosity is essential for reserve estimation.
 Determining the porosity of a reservoir rock allows for the calculation
 of the total volume of hydrocarbons that the reservoir can contain.
 This calculation is fundamental for estimating recoverable reserves, that
 is, the amount of oil and gas that can be economically extracted.
 Additionally, porosity characterizes the quality of the reservoir.
 Reservoirs with high porosity tend to be more efficient in hydrocarbon
 storage, providing more space for the fluids.
\end_layout

