\begin_layout Subsubsection
Primary Porosity and Secondary Porosity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, porosities in carbonate rocks can be classified according to
 the deposition of sedimentary materials and are referred to as primary
 and secondary porosity.
 These two types of porosity are directly interconnected in the formation
 of pore space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Primary porosity is formed during the deposition of sedimentary material
 and can be either intragranular (within grains) or intergranular (between
 grains).
 Factors influencing the formation of primary porosity include packing,
 grain size, compaction, sorting, angularity, and cementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondary porosity, also known as post-depositional porosity, arises as
 a result of geological processes occurring after the formation of the rock
 from sediments.
 These processes include fracturing, dissolution, dolomitization, and fracturing
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "flugel2010microfacies"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Secondary porosity is commonly found in carbonate rocks as it can be generated
 by processes such as dissolution, dolomitization, or fracturing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to these categories, there are various classifications based
 on pore size, which are divided into micro, meso, and macro pores.
 This study adopts the classification proposed by 
