\begin_layout Subsection
Permeability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ability of a rock to transmit fluid through its pore space is called
 permeability, a fundamental property.
 In carbonate rocks, permeability can vary considerably for the same porosity
 due to various properties of the pore space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are three types of permeability: absolute, effective, and relative.
 Absolute permeability pertains to the flow of a single non-reactive fluid,
 while effective permeability involves the flow of a fluid in the presence
 of another immiscible one.
 Relative permeability is the ratio of effective to absolute permeability.
 Equation x, presented, describes fluid flow in porous media, where variables
 such as flow rate, porous media proportionality constant, cross-sectional
 area, water heights, and porous media length are considered.
 This equation was empirically derived from a water treatment experiment
 using sand filters 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rosa2006engenharia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q=KA\frac{h_{1}-h_{2}}{L}\label{eq:Darcy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the constant K [D]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
K=\frac{\gamma k}{\mu}\label{eq:K_darcy}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
depends on the absolute permeability of the porous medium, the viscosity
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 [cP], and the specific weight of the fluid 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\frac{N}{m^{3}}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By substituting Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:K_darcy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Darcy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we obtain Darcy's law for fluids (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Darcy's Law"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
q=\frac{KA\Delta P}{\mu L}\label{eq: Darcy's Law}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As h1 and h2 have pressure units, they can be replaced by P [atm].
 The fluid viscosity is expressed in centipoise [cP] and permeability in
