\begin_layout Subsubsection
Kozeny-Carman Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Este modelo relaciona a permeabilidade de um meio poroso à sua estrutura
 e propriedades fluidas.
 A equação de Kozeny-Carman é derivada com base em uma idealização do fluxo
 de fluido através de um meio poroso, considerando-o como um conjunto de
 canais capilares tortuosos e uniformemente distribuídos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tiab2024petrophysics"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Kozeny-Carman theory can be expressed by Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kozeny Carman"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k=\frac{\phi d_{p}^{2}}{16τ}\label{eq:Kozeny Carman}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where k is the absolute permeability [mD], 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is the porosity [%], 
\begin_inset Formula $τ$
\end_inset

 is the tortuosity [
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\mu m}{\mu m}$
\end_inset

], and dp is the pores average (mean volume) diameter [
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Winland Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conforme reportado por 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kolodzie1980analysis"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Winland desenvolveu um método para calcular o tamanho médio de garganta
 de poros em suas abordagens nos campos de Weyburn, Hidalgo e Spindle.
 O modelo desenvolvido por Winland pode ser observado pela Equação 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Winland Equation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
log\,(r35)=0.732+0.588\,log\,k_{air}−\,0.864\,log\,φ\label{eq: Winland Equation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{35}$
\end_inset

 refers to the radius [
\begin_inset Formula $\mu m$
\end_inset

] of the smallest pores or throats filled with mercury at 35% saturation
 in an MIP test.
 Additionally, 
\begin_inset Formula $ϕ$
\end_inset

 represents porosity [%], and 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{air}$
