\begin_layout Section
Mercury Injection Porosimetry (MIP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Glover (2000), Mercury Intrusion Porosimetry is a widely used
 methodology for investigating pore properties.
 This method relies on the concept that mercury is a non - wetting fluid
 and cannot spontaneously fill the rock pores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, a dry sample of any shape, previously weighed, is inserted into a
 chamber to be gradually filled with mercury under different pressure levels.
 By observing a volume scale, one can deduce how the mercury level inside
 the chamber varies.
 At very low pressures, the mercury remains around the sample and does not
 penetrate the pores.
 Therefore, the increase in mercury level is related to the total volume
 of the sample.
 As the pressure increases, the mercury begins to occupy the pores, and
 a decrease in the mercury level is recorded on the scale.
 Mercury penetrates into progressively smaller pores at each stage, overcoming
 the capillary pressure acting against the non-wetting liquid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relationship between the applied pressure and the minimum pore size
 into which mercury is forced to enter is described by the Washburn Equation
 (Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Washburn model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D=\frac{-4\gamma\cos\left(\theta\right)}{P}\label{eq: Washburn model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the pore diameter, P is the applied pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is the surface tension, and 
\begin_inset Formula $θ$
\end_inset

 is the contact angle between mercury and the pore wall.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "giesche2006mercury"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Mercury porosimetry is an extremely useful characterization technique
 for porous materials.
 In his survey, the author suggests that pores between 500 
\begin_inset Formula $µm$
\end_inset

 and 3.5 
\begin_inset Formula $nm$
\end_inset

 can be investigated.
 Mercury porosimetry provides a wealth of information, such as pore size
 distribution, total pore volume or porosity, skeletal and apparent density,
 as well as the sample's surface area.
 Still according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "giesche2006mercury"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, No other porosity characterization technique can achieve this range of
 information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is worth noting that the method also has limitations.
 One of its main limitations is that mercury measures the largest entries
 towards a pore, but it doesn't measure its true internal size.
 For this reason, this technique does not allow for the analysis of closed
